The chart illustrates the proportion of households that owned various types of technology in a European country between 1997 and 2007. Overall, there was a significant increase in the ownership of all technologies shown during this period.

In 1997, mobile phones were the least common, owned by approximately 20% of households, while CD players were the most popular at around 60%. By 2007, mobile phone ownership had skyrocketed to nearly 80%, becoming the second-most owned technology after DVD players, which reached about 85%.

Computer ownership also saw substantial growth, rising from roughly 30% in 1997 to 70% in 2007. Internet access, which was negligible in 1997 at less than 10%, grew dramatically to approximately 45% by 2007, though it remained the least common technology overall.

In conclusion, the chart demonstrates a clear trend of increasing technology adoption across all categories, with mobile phones and computers showing the most dramatic growth rates during the ten-year period.
